{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17564868","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17564868"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:19:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:19:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17163"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17163","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17163"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.1,0.49,0.03,0.37]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9853"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68849"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9853","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9853"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17163"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54306"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"4340"},{"type":"tags","id":"4517"},{"type":"tags","id":"11159"},{"type":"tags","id":"11949"},{"type":"tags","id":"12799"},{"type":"tags","id":"12915"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23088"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68849","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68849"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for her first antenatal visit. She has a positive home pregnancy test and her last menstrual period was six weeks ago. She has no significant medical history and takes only folate supplements. She is a non-smoker and does not drink alcohol. This is her first pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. She requests information about first trimester screening options for chromosomal abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most accurate screening test for fetal chromosomal abnormalities?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Maternal serum screening alone","Second trimester quadruple test","Non-invasive prenatal testing","Nuchal translucency ultrasound alone","Combined first trimester screening"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFirst trimester screening for chromosomal abnormalities is an important part of routine antenatal care. Different screening modalities have varying levels of accuracy and timing considerations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-invasive prenatal testing\u003C/strong\u003E (NIPT) analyses cell-free fetal DNA in maternal blood and has the highest sensitivity (\u0026gt;99%) and specificity (\u0026gt;99%) for detecting common chromosomal abnormalities including trisomy 21, 18, and 13. It can be performed from 10 weeks gestation onwards. While it is more expensive than other screening options, it provides the most accurate results.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECombined first trimester screening\u003C/strong\u003E includes nuchal translucency ultrasound at 11-13 weeks plus maternal serum markers (pregnancy-associated plasma protein A and beta-human chorionic gonadotropin). It has a detection rate of approximately 85-90% for trisomy 21 with a 5% false positive rate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaternal serum screening\u003C/strong\u003E alone has poor sensitivity and specificity compared to other screening options. It is no longer recommended as a standalone screening test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENuchal translucency ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E alone, while an important component of combined first trimester screening, has lower accuracy than when combined with serum markers. It should not be used in isolation for chromosomal screening.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESecond trimester quadruple test\u003C/strong\u003E measures four maternal serum markers between 15-20 weeks gestation. It has lower sensitivity than first trimester screening options and provides results later in pregnancy, potentially limiting options for further testing or management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that while NIPT is the most accurate screening test, it is not diagnostic. Positive results should be confirmed with diagnostic testing such as chorionic villus sampling or amniocentesis. Additionally, genetic counselling should be offered to discuss the implications of testing and results.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Non-invasive prenatal testing (NIPT) has the highest sensitivity and specificity for common chromosomal abnormalities in first trimester screening.","NIPT can be performed from 10 weeks gestation onwards.","Combined first trimester screening includes nuchal translucency ultrasound and maternal serum markers."],"references":["Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists. Fetal anomalies: clinical guideline [Internet]. Melbourne (AU): RANZCOG; 2016 [cited 2024 Dec 10]. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/Fetal-Anomalies-Clinical-Guideline.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54306"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17163"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54306","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54306"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-10T16:23:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-10T16:24:51+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9853"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"